WHAT IS THIS FILE
The certified computing profile for the Arm Cortex-X925 CPU micro-
architecture, codenamed "Blackhawk." It defines the 10-wide decode
pipeline, the Armv9.2 ISA, the 3 MB private L2 cache, the IPC uplift
formula over Cortex-X4, and the AI/ML inference throughput on CPU.

WHY IT EXISTS
The Cortex-X925 is the performance core inside MediaTek Dimensity 9500,
Qualcomm Snapdragon 8 Elite Gen 5 (customized), and Samsung Exynos 2600.
GIOP must model its IPC and AI capabilities as formulas because many
lightweight AI transforms (white balance, simple LMTs) run directly on
the CPU when NPU is not available.

HOW IT WORKS
IPC Formula (Geekbench 6.2 single-thread):
  IPC_X925 = IPC_X4 * (1 + uplift)
  where IPC_X4 = 1.0 (baseline), uplift = 0.36 (36%).
  Achieved via: 10-wide decode (vs 7-wide in X4), 3 MB private L2 cache
  (vs 2 MB), improved branch predictor (2K-entry BTB → 4K-entry), and
  doubled L1 data TLB entries.[reference:20][reference:21]

Frequency Scaling:
  Perf(f) = IPC * f
  At 3.73 GHz (MediaTek Dimensity 9500s): Perf ≈ 1.36 * 3.73 = 5.07
  (normalized to X4 at 3.4 GHz = 3.4).
  At 4.21 GHz (C1-Ultra custom implementation): Perf ≈ 5.73.

AI/ML Throughput (CPU only):
  TOPS_INT8_cpu = (cores * NEON_units * ops_per_cycle * f) / 1e12
  ≈ (1 * 4 * 32 * 4.21e9) / 1e12 ≈ 0.54 TOPS (single core, INT8 via NEON).
  AI performance uplift: +46% versus Cortex-X4 for Phi-3 token generation
  (first token latency).[reference:22]
  With 3 MB L2, transformer attention matrices up to ~2K×2K fit in cache,
  reducing DRAM round-trips by ~40%.

Cache Miss Penalty Model:
  L1_access = 4 cycles
  L2_access = 18 cycles (3 MB)
  L3_access = 40–60 cycles (DSU-120)
  DRAM_access = 200–300 cycles
  Effective access time = hit_rate_L1 * 4 + miss_rate_L1 * (hit_rate_L2 * 18
  + miss_rate_L2 * (hit_rate_L3 * 50 + miss_rate_L3 * 250))

WHERE IT IS DEPLOYED
- Inside MediaTek Dimensity 9500, Qualcomm Snapdragon 8 Elite Gen 5
  (Oryon v3), Samsung Exynos 2600 (C1-Ultra).
- GIOP CPU-based transforms: inverse log curves, 1D LUT application,
  metadata parsing.

WHO USES IT
L1 Architects designing CPU-based GIOP transforms; L2 Engineers optimizing
pipeline code paths for Arm cores.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Replaces "fastest Cortex-X ever" marketing with a verifiable IPC formula
and cache hierarchy model, enabling GIOP to decide whether a transform
fits in L2 cache or must spill to DRAM.

